---
import Layout from "@/components/Layout.astro";
import { propagation, meta } from "@/lib/load";
import { formatDate } from "@/lib/format";
import { withBase } from "@/lib/paths";

const corpusStart = meta.corpusStart ? formatDate(meta.corpusStart) : "November 2025";

const tierCounts: Record<"added" | "present-at-start" | "tied", number> = {
  added: 0,
  "present-at-start": 0,
  tied: 0,
};
for (const c of propagation.clusters) {
  const t = c.firstObserved?.tier;
  if (t) tierCounts[t] += 1;
}
---

<Layout
  title="Reading the data"
  description="How to read the similarity scores, originality figures, reuse heat-map and passage provenance on this site — and what each of them does not claim."
>
  <div class="page reading prose stack">
    <h1>Reading the data</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      This site turns a stack of government web pages into numbers and colours:
      similarity scores, originality figures, a reuse heat-map, and a record of
      which statement we saw a passage in first. Here is what each one means
      &mdash; and, just as importantly, what it does not.
    </p>

    <h2 id="corpus">When the record starts</h2>
    <p>
      Continuous tracking opens in November 2025, at the launch of the Australian
      Public Service&rsquo;s AI Plan. This tracker was begun live, from a laptop in
      the audience, as the plan was unveiled &mdash; which is why the record starts
      exactly when it does. The earliest snapshot is timestamped {corpusStart}.
    </p>
    <p>
      The <em>Policy for the responsible use of AI in government</em> has required
      these statements since February 2025, so their first nine months &mdash; when
      most agencies drafted, published and borrowed from one another &mdash; happened
      before the tracker was watching. Every statement that already existed enters
      the record together on day one, marked &ldquo;first tracked&rdquo; rather than
      &ldquo;published&rdquo;: we don&rsquo;t know what those statements looked like
      before we first saw them. This is the single biggest limit on everything below.
    </p>

    <h2 id="reuse">Shared passages and the reuse heat-map</h2>
    <p>
      Agencies reuse one another&rsquo;s wording heavily. On each statement page,
      every passage is tinted by how widely the same words appear across all the
      statements we track:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>uncoloured</strong> &mdash; unique to that statement;</li>
      <li><strong>a few</strong> &mdash; shared with two or three other agencies;</li>
      <li><strong>several</strong> &mdash; shared with four to nine;</li>
      <li><strong>many</strong> &mdash; shared with ten to twenty-four;</li>
      <li><strong>most</strong> &mdash; shared with twenty-five or more.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Wording lifted straight from the Policy is always tinted at least lightly. A
      passage that also appears in the Digital Transformation Agency&rsquo;s own
      statement is marked <em>in DTA template</em>, because the DTA publishes the
      wording most other agencies start from.
    </p>
    <h3 id="first-observed">First observed in our corpus</h3>
    <p>
      For every shared passage we also record which tracked statement showed it
      earliest, and the order the others picked it up. Each passage falls into one
      of three tiers, by how much weight that ordering can bear:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>added during tracking</strong> ({tierCounts.added}) &mdash; we watched
        the first agency add the passage well after the record opened, then watched
        others follow. The strongest signal.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>present at the start</strong> ({tierCounts["present-at-start"]}) &mdash;
        the first agency already had the passage when tracking began; others adopted it
        later. We can order the latecomers, but not that first agency&rsquo;s own source.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>tied</strong> ({tierCounts.tied}) &mdash; several agencies share the
        earliest date, usually because they were all present on day one, so we make no
        claim about order.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Read this as <em>first observed by us</em>, never as proof of who wrote it
      first. A passage two agencies both carried on day one cannot be ordered at all,
      and even a clean ordering only says who we saw with it first. The real source
      could be an agency we don&rsquo;t track, an internal draft circulated off the
      web, or the DTA template itself.
    </p>

    <h2 id="originality">Originality scores</h2>
    <p>
      A statement&rsquo;s originality score is the share of its text, weighted by
      length, that is <em>not</em> shared with other agencies and <em>not</em> drawn
      from the template. A statement at 80% is mostly in its own words; one at 20% is
      mostly shared or templated language. The leaderboard and the agency grid colour
      each statement on this scale, from borrowed to bespoke.
    </p>
    <p>
      The DTA scores low by design: it publishes the template, so almost everything
      it says is, by definition, shared. We label it the template source rather than
      reading its low score as a lack of effort.
    </p>

    <h2 id="similarity">Similarity</h2>
    <p>
      Similarity is a different measurement from reuse. Reuse is literal &mdash; the
      same words, matched exactly. Similarity is about meaning: each statement is
      turned into a numeric fingerprint (an embedding) and compared with every other,
      so two statements can score as similar even when they share no identical
      passages, simply because they cover the same ground in the same way. The
      similarity map and the &ldquo;reads most like&rdquo; lists use this measure.
      Scores run from 0 to 1; closer to 1 means more alike.
    </p>

    <h2 id="more">The fine print</h2>
    <p>
      For how all of this is computed &mdash; how spurious scrape churn is collapsed
      out, the exact passage-matching rules, the embedding model &mdash; and for the
      limits of the scraping itself, see the methodology and caveats on the <a
        href={withBase("/about")}>About page</a
      >.
    </p>
  </div>
</Layout>

<style>
  .reading {
    max-width: 46rem;
  }

  .reading h3 {
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    margin-block-start: var(--space-4);
  }
</style>
